23/08/24, 10:03â€¯am - +91 63978 15129: Dear Students of CET,

Greetings from the Computer Engineering Student Society (CESS)!

We are delighted to introduce ourselves as the one and only official society for computer engineering students at G.N.D.U. 
Our main goal is to provide a platform for students like you to participate in various events and activities, and enhance your skills beyond the academic curriculum.

CESS stands for *Computer Engineering Student Society* where we are dedicated to creating a strong community of like-minded individuals who share a passion for technology. 

As a member of CESS, you will have the opportunity to join various clubs as follows  
*Tech Titans, The Sargam , The Literary Club, The Placement Club, The Buzz, The Cinematics, Arts n Craft , The Boosters , The Theatre Club , The Fusion Club*
These clubs are designed to cater to diverse interests and help you showcase your all-rounder personality.

Our sole purpose is to provide you with a platform to _learn, grow, and excel_ together!!

By joining CESS, you will not only have the chance to participate in exciting events and competitions, but also the opportunity to decorate your resume showcasing diverse skills and experiences.

We would love to have you as a part of our community and help you make the most of your college experience. 

Don't miss this chance to be a part of something bigger and join CESS asap!! The enrollment for which is through interviews .

Join CESS - Your Gateway to Diverse Opportunities!
We look forward to having you on board!!

Best regards,
Computer Engineering Student Society (CESS)
Guru Nanak Dev University,  Amritsar.

- Pentagon with 30 mm sides.

- The whole pentagonâ€™s plane inclined at 30Â° to VP.

 Steps:

1. *Top View (HP):**
   - Draw the pentagon with 30 mm sides.
   - Incline side AB at 45Â° to a reference line.

2. *Front View (VP):*
   - Project lines from the top view to the front view.
   - Incline the pentagonâ€™s plane by 30Â°.
Iske saath dono projections miljayegi
Aur conclusion mein

Top view: A pentagon with side AB inclined at 45Â° to HP

.Front view: A distorted pentagon inclined at 30Â° to VP.

24/09/24, 9:39â€¯am - +91 6284 402 971: Steps to download Fee Receipt from SLC Fee Portal:
1.	Open SLC Portal Link: https://slc.gndu.ac.in/Integration/StudentArea/Login2021.aspx
2.	Login using your 13-digit Student ID and Password used at the time of admission for filling up Application Form.
3.	Important if your have Student ID and forgotten password: https://collegeadmissions.gndu.ac.in/studentArea/StuForgetPass.aspx
4.	After successfully logging in, select Payment History Option under the Payments Menu
5.	Click on Print Receipt button to print Reciept. 
*Follow same procedure irrespective of Mode of Payment i.e. Online / Bank Challan / Cash*

09/03/25, 10:53â€¯am - Kavyansh GNDU: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#define int long long
 
 
void solve() {
    int n;
    cin >> n;
    std::vector<int> a(n);
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        cin >> a[i];
    }
    
    int ans = 0;
    for(int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
        ans = max(ans , a[i] * a[i + 1]);
    }
    cout << ans << "\n";
    
}
 
 
 
signed main() {
    std::ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    std::cin.tie(nullptr);
    
    int t;
    std::cin >> t;
    
    while (t--) {
        solve();
    }
    
    return 0;
}

10/03/25, 7:27â€¯pm - Gurjot Singh Bhullar GNDU: Medicine and Genetic Research: Promise and Problems
Early Progress (1970s)

Since the 1970s, medicine has improved a lot because of genetic research. Scientists found genes that cause serious illnesses and birth defects. This led to tests that can help people know if they or their children might have genetic problems.

For example, tests like amniocentesis can check unborn babies for genetic diseases. In the case of Huntingtonâ€™s disease, a fatal condition, some people choose not to have children to avoid passing it on since there is a 50% chance their child might inherit it. These tests have helped slow the spread of some diseases.

Fast Progress in the 1990s

In the 1990s, genetic research grew quickly because of more funding from companies and research institutions. This money allowed scientists to make big advancements.

For instance, in 2000, doctors in France treated three babies with a rare immune deficiency by adding a healthy gene to their bone marrow. Within ten months, their immune systems worked like normal. This success gave hope that genetic research could save many lives.

Problems with Genetic Research

Although there were some great results, there were also many problems:

Overpromising Results:
Researchers claimed they would soon cure diseases like cystic fibrosis and cancer. However, these claims were too optimistic since their successes were mostly with simpler cases and a small number of patients.
Rushed Trials:
Some trials started before there was enough proof that the treatments were safe. This caused poor results, and in some cases, harm. For example, an 18-year-old died because his immune system reacted badly during a trial. This showed the danger of rushing into testing without proper safety checks.
Pressure from Companies:
Biotech companies wanted quick results to make profits, so they pushed researchers to start trials early. To keep their funding, some researchers understated the risks, which sometimes put participants in danger.
A Safer Approach

After these issues, researchers became more careful:

They now make sure treatments are safe before testing on people.
They donâ€™t exaggerate small successes in trials.
For example, new treatments for sickle cell disease using tools like CRISPR show promise, but scientists warn that more testing is needed. Similarly, experimental therapies have helped some people with hereditary blindness regain vision, but these treatments are not yet widely available.

Hope for the Future

Even though there are challenges, genetic research has huge potential. Scientists believe it can one day help treat big illnesses like cancer, diabetes, and heart disease. However, they say it will take timeâ€”sometimes years or even decades.

The success of mRNA vaccines for COVID-19 shows how genetic research can solve big health problems. This proves that with careful research, genetic medicine can help improve and save lives.

Conclusion

Genetic medicine is powerful and can transform healthcare. But progress must be careful and safe. With continued research, we can hope for a future where genetic diseases are prevented or even eliminated, helping people live healthier lives.
10/03/25, 7:27â€¯pm - Gurjot Singh Bhullar GNDU: Heart Disease and the Impact of Changing Attitudes on Health
In the late 20th century, medical research revealed that heart disease is closely linked to lifestyle factors such as stress, smoking, poor nutrition, and lack of exercise. This understanding led doctors and health experts to emphasize prevention by encouraging individuals to take proactive steps to reduce their risk of heart disease. Over time, people began to realize the strong connection between lifestyle choices and heart health, which sparked a significant shift in public attitudes.
Previously, people relied heavily on doctors for treatment, believing that access to medical care was sufficient to maintain health. However, today there is a growing awareness that simply receiving treatment is not enough. Individuals are now taking greater responsibility for their health by adopting healthier habits. This shift is reflected in several behavioral changes since the 1970s, particularly in countries like the United States. For example, smoking rates have dropped considerably, with fewer people taking up the habit. Public awareness of the dangers of smoking has been instrumental in this decline.
In addition to quitting smoking, people have become more serious about managing stress, improving their diets, and engaging in regular physical activity such as walking, running, and swimming. Some even choose to walk or bike to work instead of driving or using public transportation, recognizing the health benefits of staying active.
These changes in attitude and behavior have had a positive impact on public health. Since the 1950s, the number of deaths from heart disease per 100,000 people has significantly decreased. While advancements in medical technology have improved diagnosis and treatment, experts agree that a large portion of this improvement is due to a better-educated public that understands the importance of prevention.
Additional Insights: The growing focus on prevention highlights the critical role of education and public health campaigns in promoting healthier lifestyles. Schools, workplaces, and government policies have all contributed to this change by supporting wellness programs, offering healthier food options, and implementing smoking bans in public areas. Furthermore, access to affordable healthcare and regular check-ups allows people to monitor their health and address potential heart risks early on.
In conclusion, the decline in heart disease rates is a testament to the power of changing attitudes toward health. By making healthier lifestyle choices and taking responsibility for their well-being, people are actively reducing their risk of heart disease. This positive trend, coupled with medical advancements, continues to improve heart health outcomes globally. However, ongoing efforts to promote awareness and prevention are necessary to ensure this progress continues
10/03/25, 7:27â€¯pm - Gurjot Singh Bhullar GNDU: Cardiovascular Disease: Causes and Methods to Reduce Risk (10 Marks)
Cardiovascular disease (CVD), which includes heart disease, high blood pressure, and strokes, remains one of the leading causes of death worldwide. Despite significant medical advances, CVD continues to pose a threat, especially as it increasingly affects both developed and developing nations.
1. Causes of Cardiovascular Disease:
    * Unhealthy Diet: Diets high in saturated fats, sugars, and salt can lead to high cholesterol, high blood pressure, and weight gainâ€”all major risk factors for CVD.
    * Lack of Physical Activity: Sedentary lifestyles reduce heart health and increase the likelihood of obesity, which is linked to heart disease.
    * Smoking and Alcohol: Smoking damages blood vessels and increases the risk of heart attacks and strokes, while excessive alcohol intake can lead to high blood pressure.
    * Stress: Chronic stress can raise blood pressure, contribute to unhealthy behaviors (e.g., overeating, smoking), and increase the risk of heart disease.
    * Genetic Factors: Family history of heart disease may increase an individual's risk of developing CVD.
2. Methods to Reduce Risk:
    * Healthy Eating: A diet rich in fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean proteins, and healthy fats (like omega-3 fatty acids) can reduce cholesterol and blood pressure, lowering the risk of heart disease.
    * Regular Exercise: Engaging in at least 150 minutes of moderate-intensity physical activity per week strengthens the heart, improves circulation, and helps maintain a healthy weight.
    * Avoid Smoking and Limit Alcohol: Quitting smoking and reducing alcohol intake are crucial steps in lowering the risk of heart disease. Smoking cessation not only reduces immediate heart risks but also improves overall cardiovascular health.
    * Stress Management: Techniques like meditation, yoga, deep breathing exercises, and regular relaxation activities can help manage stress, lowering its negative effects on the heart.
    * Regular Health Screenings: Monitoring blood pressure, cholesterol levels, and blood sugar levels through regular check-ups can help in early detection and management of risk factors.
3. In conclusion, preventing cardiovascular disease involves making conscious lifestyle changes, such as maintaining a healthy diet, exercising regularly, avoiding harmful habits like smoking, and managing stress. Alongside medical advancements, these preventative measures can significantly reduce the global burden of CVD.

28/05/25, 2:11â€¯pm - Ayush Sahani GNDU: # ğŸ“˜ **UNIT 1 â€“ WORLD HEALTH IN THE TWENTY-FIRST CENTURY**

---

## ğŸ”¹ READING 1: *Heart Disease and Changing Attitudes*

### **Q1. How have people's attitudes towards heart disease changed over time? Explain with reasons.**

**Answer:**
In earlier times, heart disease was considered a sudden and unavoidable illness. People believed that it affected only older or unlucky individuals and could not be predicted. However, in recent decades, attitudes have shifted significantly due to medical research and public awareness.

Now, it is known that heart disease is closely linked to lifestyle factors such as diet, stress, lack of exercise, and smoking. This understanding has led to the promotion of preventive healthcare practices. Campaigns encourage healthy living, routine checkups, and physical activity.

Thus, the approach has changed from passive acceptance to active prevention, where individuals are encouraged to take responsibility for their heart health.

---

## ğŸ”¹ READING 2: *Cardiovascular Disease: A Good News â€“ Bad News Story*

### **Q2. Cardiovascular disease is both a serious threat and a hopeful opportunity. Discuss.**

**Answer:**
Cardiovascular disease (CVD) remains the leading cause of death globally. This is the "bad news"â€”millions of lives are affected each year by heart attacks, strokes, and related conditions.

However, the "good news" is that with medical advancements and lifestyle changes, CVD is now largely preventable. Public health education, better nutrition, exercise, and early detection through technology have significantly reduced mortality rates.

This dual reality makes CVD a challenge but also an opportunityâ€”if individuals adopt healthy habits and societies invest in healthcare, this major killer can be controlled. Hence, awareness and access are key.

---

## ğŸ”¹ READING 3: *Medicine and Genetic Research: Promise and Problems*

### **Q3. Discuss the potential and problems of genetic research in modern medicine.**

**Answer:**
Genetic research offers exciting opportunities in the medical world. Using tools like CRISPR, scientists can edit genes to potentially cure hereditary diseases such as sickle cell anemia, cancer, and cystic fibrosis. This marks a revolutionary step in personalized medicine.

However, this advancement comes with challenges. The treatment is expensive and mostly available in developed nations, creating a gap between rich and poor. There are also ethical concernsâ€”should we allow people to design their babies? Could this lead to genetic discrimination?

In conclusion, while genetic research holds immense promise, it must be handled with regulation, fairness, and awareness to avoid abuse and inequality.

---

## ğŸ”¹ READING 4: *AIDS â€“ Not Someone Elseâ€™s Problem*

### **Q4. Why is AIDS a global issue and not just someone elseâ€™s problem? Explain.**

**Answer:**
AIDS is a disease that affects people across all regions, classes, and cultures. In its early years, it was falsely assumed to only affect certain communities. This led to ignorance, stigma, and lack of action.

However, it is now clear that AIDS is a global health crisis. Anyone can contract it if unaware or unprotected. The real danger lies not just in the disease itself, but in the **social stigma** attached to it. This prevents people from getting tested, talking openly, and accessing care.

Therefore, the battle against AIDS requires compassion, awareness, and education. It is not someone elseâ€™s problemâ€”it concerns us all.

---

# ğŸ“˜ **UNIT 2 â€“ LIVING IN A MULTICULTURAL SOCIETY**

---

## ğŸ”¹ READING 1: *The Age of Immigration*

### **Q5. Why is the 21st century called the Age of Immigration? What are its effects on society?**

**Answer:**
The 21st century has seen a massive rise in global migration. People move across countries seeking safety, better jobs, education, and a higher quality of life. Wars, poverty, climate change, and global opportunities have fueled this movement.

This has made many nations multiculturalâ€”where people of different cultures, languages, and religions live together. Immigration has contributed to innovation, economic growth, and cultural richness.

However, it also brings challenges: racism, cultural clashes, and political tension. Thus, the "Age of Immigration" is marked by both opportunities and responsibilities for society.

---

## ğŸ”¹ READING 2: *Who Are Todayâ€™s Immigrants?*

### **Q6. Describe the profile of modern immigrants. How are myths about them misleading?**

**Answer:**
Todayâ€™s immigrants are diverseâ€”many are skilled professionals, students, or entrepreneurs. They contribute to the economy, bring new ideas, and enrich culture.

However, there are several myths: that immigrants steal jobs, increase crime, or are illegal. These beliefs are mostly false and based on fear or politics.

Modern immigrants are often more hardworking and educated than locals. Breaking these stereotypes is important for building inclusive and just societies.

---

## ğŸ”¹ READING 3: *Views on Multiculturalism*

### **Q7. What are the advantages and disadvantages of multiculturalism?**

**Answer:**
Multiculturalism refers to a society that embraces people from different cultural backgrounds. Its advantages include cultural exchange, creativity, tolerance, and global awareness. People learn new languages, try diverse foods, and celebrate various traditions.

However, it also brings challenges. People may struggle with identity, face racism, or experience cultural misunderstandings. Host societies may feel their native culture is being diluted.

The key is balance. Through education, dialogue, and policies that promote integration, multiculturalism can be a powerful force for unity and growth.

---

## ğŸ”¹ READING 4: *Experimental Evidence on the Nature of Prejudice*

### **Q8. What do experiments reveal about the nature of prejudice? Can it be removed?**

**Answer:**
Research shows that prejudice is **learned**, not inborn. Children develop bias by observing adults and media. Experiments with children prove that they can be taught to hateâ€”or to loveâ€”based on what society shows them.

While prejudice may not be eliminated completely, it can be greatly reduced. Intercultural contact, education, empathy training, and positive media can help.

The key is consistency and long-term exposure to diverse people. Over time, minds can changeâ€”and so can society.

29/09/25, 12:58â€¯pm - +91 79732 73978: Stack : 

#define MAX 5
int stack[MAX], top = -1;

void push(int x) {
   if(top == MAX-1) cout << "Overflow";
   else stack[++top] = x;
}

void pop() {
   if(top == -1) cout << "Underflow";
   else top--;
}

int peek() {
   if(top == -1) cout << "Empty";
   else return stack[top];
}


Queue :

#define MAX 5
int queue[MAX], front = -1, rear = -1;

void enqueue(int x) {
   if(rear == MAX-1) cout << "Overflow";
   else {
      if(front == -1) front = 0;
      queue[++rear] = x;
   }
}

void dequeue() {
   if(front == -1 || front > rear) cout << "Underflow";
   else front++;
}

int peek() {
   if(front == -1 || front > rear) cout << "Empty";
   else return queue[front];
}

30/09/25, 1:44â€¯pm - +91 83602 74757: #include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int n, first = 0, second = 1, next;

    cout << "Enter the number of terms: ";
    cin >> n;

    cout << "Fibonacci Series: ";

    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        cout << first << " ";
        next = first + second;
        first = second;
        second = next;
    }

    cout << endl;
    return 0;
}

25/10/25, 4:00â€¯pm - +91 90173 90908: HOW TO REGISTER FOR ALL EVENTS EXCEPT THE HACKATHON ON THE WEBSITE

Go to https://spectra.cess-gndu.com/
And sign up/sign in

1. Click on "get tickets" button which you can see straight after opening the website
2. Click on the event of your choice
3. If on the phone scroll down and click "get tickets", if on the desktop "get tickets" button would be visible as such.
4. Fill in the name under which you will make the payment and the corresponding phone number and scan the QR code to pay and click Request Ticket
5. Go back to https://spectra.cess-gndu.com/
6. On the top right corner in the navbar click the circle having the initials of your name, that will take you to your profile 
7. There you will see all your tickets, some might be under processing which means our team will verify your payment first before approving your ticket, once approved your ticket would show up there and you can download it + join the WhatsApp group then

01/11/25, 11:27â€¯pm - +91 95969 14707: ğŸ•Šï¸ CESS Presents â€” *Spectra Model United Nations 2025* 

Organised by: Computer Engineering Studentsâ€™ Society (CESS), Official Student Society of the Department of Computer Science and Technology, Guru Nanak Dev University, Amritsar.

ğŸŒ *Committee Details* 

 *1. United Nations General Assembly â€“ DISEC (Disarmament and International Security Committee)* ğŸ›¡ï¸

This committee focuses on pressing global peace and security issues such as the Russiaâ€“Ukraine conflict, Israelâ€“Palestine crisis, and Indiaâ€“Pakistan tensions.

ğŸ•Šï¸ Formal Agenda:

 _â€œDeliberation on the Escalation of Global Conflicts and Measures for Sustainable International Peace and Security.â€_ 

Details:

Total Seats: 50

Representation Mode: Hybrid (some countries may have one delegate, while others may have two)

Participation Type: Individual or Team (up to 2 members per country, with prior intimation to the coordinators)

2. *International Press Corps (IPC)* ğŸ“°

For participants who want to explore journalism and media diplomacy. Delegates act as international correspondents covering committee proceedings, writing reports, and conducting interviews.


Details:

Total Seats: 10

Participation Type: Individual

Role: Press coverage, interviews, and daily releases during the event.

ğŸ’µ *Fee Structure* (Prepayment Event)
Tier	Fee (â‚¹)	Inclusions

 *Basic Delegate Pass* :	â‚¹150	Participation Kit + Certificate


ğŸ“¸ Participants must attach the payment screenshot in the registration form.

ğŸ§­ *Participation & Eligibility* 

 *Mode* : Offline at Guru Nanak Dev University, Amritsar

 *Eligibility* : Open to all GNDU students and students from other institutions as well

 *Country Allotment* : Based on first-come-first-serve registration and committee preferences

 *Hybrid Delegation Option* : 1 or 2 delegates may represent a single country (upon request after individual registration)

ğŸ“‹ *Registration Process*

ğŸ’¬ FAQ Section

1. *What is a Model United Nations (MUN)?* 

A Model UN is a simulation of the United Nations where students represent different countries and discuss international issues through diplomacy, debate, and negotiation. It helps enhance leadership, research, and public-speaking skills.


2. *Who can participate?* 
Students from any department or institution are welcome to participate. MUN is open to both GNDU students and external participants.


3. *What if I donâ€™t know how an MUN works?* 
No worries! An online orientation session will be held before the event to explain everything â€” from the format, rules, and dress code to how debates and caucuses work.


4. *Can I participate with a friend?* 
Yes. You may form a team of two delegates representing one country. However, both delegates must register individually and later inform the coordinators about their team formation.


5. *What does â€œHybrid Delegationâ€ mean?* 
It means that while some countries will have single delegates, others may have two, depending on the complexity of representation and registration volume.


6. *What is the mode of payment?* 
Prepayment is mandatory. Details will be shared along with the form link. A payment screenshot must be uploaded in the registration form.


7. *What will I get as a participant?* 
All delegates will receive a participation kit, official certificate, and refreshments or meals (based on the selected fee tier). The experience and certificate are valuable additions to your CV and portfolio.


8. *How many seats are available?* 

UNGA-DISEC: 50 seats

International Press Corps (IPC): 10 seats
Seats will be allotted strictly on a first-come-first-serve basis.

9. *How will countries be allotted?* 

After registration and payment confirmation, countries will be assigned based on availability and diversity of representation.


10. *Is there any dress code?* 

Yes. Participants are expected to follow formal Western or Indian business attire to maintain decorum and diplomatic standards.
